issue.body:
The table evaluating different choices of null values in [the _Using problematic null values_ section of the _Formatting Problems_ episode](https://datacarpentry.org/spreadsheet-ecology-lesson/02-common-mistakes/index.html#-using-problematic-null-values) is currently a screenshot from the PDF of [the paper it was originally published in](https://ojs.library.queensu.ca/index.php/IEE/article/view/4608). 

This format is not accessible to people accessing the lesson with a screen reader, and it is very difficult to capture all the information in the table as alt-text to the image. I believe the screenshot should be replaced with an HTML table containing the same information.

Note that there is [an identical issue in the _Data Organization in Spreadsheets for Social Scientists_ lesson repository](https://github.com/datacarpentry/spreadsheets-socialsci/issues/151), and another in [the Library Carpentry _Tidy Data for Librarians_ lesson repository](https://github.com/LibraryCarpentry/lc-spreadsheets/issues/124), which should be addressed simultaneously. The Library Carpentry repository issue also includes some suggestions for how the descriptions in the table could be improved when converting the screenshot.

The big question is how to deal with the 1000's of extra files that got added in bd8b003b3428d25e67417dfb0302a1934db26fe4. issue.title: CW for personal posts
issue.body:
Suggested on Mastodon and also something I thought about adding.

CW for more personal/family posts.

It depends a lot on how much "science only" we want impose it to be.
Do people come to Mastodon (or Twitter before) just to find science? I'm not sure.

I'm half a mind for, and the other against.
Maybe do a poll on Mastodon at some point.

comment.body: This feels problematic to me if we want to create a diverse and inclusive community. It feels counter to the idea of "bring your whole self" and I worry it would end up being a rule that institutionalizes the "just stick to the science" critiques that are often directed at minoritized groups speaking out about broader issues in the sciences and their everyday lives from their science focused social media accounts. Mastodon already has challenges in this space (see, e.g., [this Twitter thread by Chanda Prescod-Weinstein](https://twitter.com/IBJIYONGI/status/1590462702983720962) and this [nice post by a Mastodon vet](https://scholar.social/@CaribenxMarciaX/109313395721835492)). I'd like to avoid us reinforcing them.

It depends a lot on how much "science only" we want impose it to be.

comment.body: This feels problematic to me if we want to create a diverse and inclusive community. This looks good to me, but let's @Juniper Simonis have a look since it's their changes that are getting updated.

The big question is how to deal with the 1000's of extra files that got added in bd8b003b3428d25e67417dfb0302a1934db26fe4. If we just deleted them in a new commit we're going to end up carrying around about a gig of files in the history forever, so I'd like to get rid of them entirely. It's a littletricky because there are changes tied up in that commit that we want to keep (though I think it's only one meaningful line).

Proposal (which I think may work but we'd have to test):

1. Interactive rebase to drop bd8b003b3428d25e67417dfb0302a1934db26fe4
2. Add a new commit with the one line change that is the core of that commit
3. git filter-repo to scrub those directories from the tree (something like `git filter-repo --path forecasts/ --path resources/ --invert-paths`)
4. Force push this into main (after turning off the branch protection temporarily)
5. Then rebase your current branch or cherry-pick https://github.com/weecology/portal-forecast-web/pull/41/commits/2d4d202d522411edea25df57c2f395410deb2bad into a new one to integrate your fixes.

Thoughts?

issue.title: CW for personal posts
issue.body:
Suggested on Mastodon and also something I thought about adding.

CW for more personal/family posts.

It depends a lot on how much "science only" we want impose it to be.
Do people come to Mastodon (or Twitter before) just to find science? I'm not sure.

I'm half a mind for, and the other against.
Maybe do a poll on Mastodon at some point.

comment.body: This feels problematic to me if we want to create a diverse and inclusive community. It feels counter to the idea of "bring your whole self" and I worry it would end up being a rule that institutionalizes the "just stick to the science" critiques that are often directed at minoritized groups speaking out about broader issues in the sciences and their everyday lives from their science focused social media accounts. Mastodon already has challenges in this space (see, e.g., [this Twitter thread by Chanda Prescod-Weinstein](https://twitter.com/IBJIYONGI/status/1590462702983720962) and this [nice post by a Mastodon vet](https://scholar.social/@CaribenxMarciaX/109313395721835492)). I'd like to avoid us reinforcing them.
